 Julie Dugdale&nbsp;</b><b>- Enseignant-Chercheur&nbsp;</b><b>- LIG -&nbsp;=
&nbsp;"Social media and SMS in crisis situations"</b></div><div>In recent y=
ears our&nbsp;society has seen the enormous growth and popularity of social=
 media sites such&nbsp;as FaceBook and Twitter. These, coupled with the&nbs=
p;increased use of smart phones&nbsp;and other mobile devices, have radical=
ly changed the way that individuals interact&nbsp;and communicate. Within t=
he crisis&nbsp;management domain these tools are being&nbsp;adopted and exp=
loited by both crisis managers and citizens alike. Recent&nbsp;large-scale =
emergencies, such as&nbsp;the Haiti Earthquake gave rise to an&nbsp;unprece=
dented surge of citizen involvement where humanitarian workers tried to&nbs=
p;cope with massive amounts of&nbsp;information provided by citizens throug=
h web&nbsp;portals, platforms, and new social networking media, such as SMS=
 feeds,&nbsp;Twitter, etc. Such is the&nbsp;increase of citizen participati=
on that current crisis&nbsp;management information systems, e.g. the SAHANA=
 Open Source Disaster Management&nbsp;System and&nbsp;the crowd-sourcing pl=
atform Ushaidi, now purposely provide ways to&nbsp;incorporate information =
sent by citizens through social media and SMS. This&nbsp;presentation&nbsp;=
will examine the use and applicability of social media in crisis management=
&nbsp;from both the citizens and crisis managers=92 point of view,&nbsp;and=
 explore some of&nbsp;the challenges faced by its adoption.</div></div></di=
